# NorthNarrow — process comm allowlist OPERATOR OVERLAY (example)
#
# Beta Step 3. This is a TEMPLATE. To activate it, copy it to the live
# overlay path and edit:
#
#     cp /etc/northnarrow/process-comm-allowlist.local.example \
#        /etc/northnarrow/process-comm-allowlist.local
#
# The agent merges this overlay on top of the shipped
# `process-comm-allowlist.v1` default at boot. Unlike the `.v1` file,
# entries here carry a prefix:
#
#     +comm   ADD comm to the allowlist (exempt it from R011..R017)
#     -comm   RE-ENABLE detection on a comm that `.v1` allowlists
#
# Blank lines and `#` comments are ignored. Comms are BARE process
# names as the kernel reports them — TASK_COMM_LEN-truncated to 15
# chars (e.g. `containerd-shim-runc-v2` is reported as
# `containerd-shim`). Every change here is logged at boot.
#
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# CONTAINER RUNTIMES — uncomment ONLY on a host that runs containers
# (Docker, Kubernetes, podman, containerd, CRI-O).
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# SECURITY IMPLICATION — READ BEFORE ENABLING:
#
#   R013 (Namespace/escape tooling, MITRE T1611 Escape-to-Host) fires
#   when `runc` execs from a NON-standard path (a dropped/modified runc
#   in /tmp, /dev/shm, a writable bundle dir, …) — the exact shape of
#   the CVE-2019-5736 runc-overwrite breakout. Adding `+runc` below
#   exempts `runc` from R013 EVERYWHERE on this host, including those
#   non-standard paths. Only enable it where legitimate container
#   activity is producing R013 false positives, and prefer tightening
#   the path set over a blanket exemption if you can.
#
#   Note: of the comms below, only `runc` is currently an R013 target;
#   the others never trip R013 and are listed for parity / forward
#   compatibility with future container-aware rules. They are harmless
#   to enable but also unnecessary for silencing R013 today.
#
# Uncomment the lines that match your runtime:
#
#+runc
#+crun
#+containerd-shim
#+conmon
#+docker-init
#+dumb-init

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# SITE-SPECIFIC EXEMPTIONS — add trusted-actor comms here, each with a
# comment explaining WHY it is trusted (so the next operator/auditor
# understands the exemption).
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# Example:
#   +my-deploy-tool   # in-house provisioning agent, sets caps on deploy
